---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---
<Base
  title="Run it locally — Helix"
  description="Run Helix on your own machine. Verify the whole trust core from a clean clone in about a minute on any CPU — or serve a real GPT-2 model live on your own NVIDIA GPU, on a toolchain compiled from 299 hand-typed bytes. No GPU? Download the offline demo and run it in your browser."
>
  <section class="page-hero dark">
    <div class="wrap">
      <span class="eyebrow">run it yourself · on your own machine</span>
      <h1>Don&rsquo;t take our word for it. <em>Run it.</em></h1>
      <p class="lede">Everything here is public and reproducible. There are three ways in, from zero effort to the full live model: open the demo in your browser, verify the entire trust core from a clean clone in about a minute, or serve a real GPT-2 generating live on your own GPU — on a compiler you can rebuild from 299 hand-typed bytes.</p>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/helix-demo.zip" download>Download the demo <span class="arrow">&darr;</span></a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="https://github.com/Questeria/helix">View the repository <span class="arrow">&rarr;</span></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PATH 1 — the offline demo, for everyone -->
  <section>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="split">
        <div class="split-label">
          <span class="eyebrow">no install · any browser</span>
          <h2>1 · Open the demo offline</h2>
          <p>The whole demo is plain HTML and JavaScript with no dependencies. Download it, unzip it, and open <code>landing.html</code>. It runs entirely on your machine, offline, and phones home to nobody.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>The download has no AI backend bundled with it, so it is honest about what it shows:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>The Guided Run replays a real recorded run</strong> of GPT-2-XL (1.5B) executing on Helix-compiled GPU kernels — the tokens, the per-layer trace, and the 25/25 verification are the genuine recorded output, committed as data. The badge reads <strong>REPLAY</strong>.</li>
            <li><strong>Type your own prompt</strong> with no backend and the page animates the run&rsquo;s <em>structure</em> with simulated numbers, clearly badged <strong>PREVIEW — simulated</strong>. The demo is built so a mock can never be mistaken for a real model.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>To run a model <em>live</em> instead of replaying one, keep reading.</p>
          <div class="btn-row">
            <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/helix-demo.zip" download>Download <code>helix-demo.zip</code> <span class="arrow">&darr;</span></a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PATH 2 — verify the trust core, CPU-only -->
  <section class="dark">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="split">
        <div class="split-label">
          <span class="eyebrow">~1 minute · CPU-only · no GPU, no weights</span>
          <h2>2 · Verify the trust core</h2>
          <p>This is the part anyone can reproduce from the repository alone. On a clean checkout it deletes every pre-built binary, rebuilds the entire ladder from raw, runs the self-host fixpoint and the gcc diverse double-compile, asserts the pinned anchors, and exits nonzero on any mismatch.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="prose">
          <div class="code-card">
            <div class="code-head">
              <div class="dots" aria-hidden="true"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
              <span>clean checkout · trust core · fail-closed</span>
            </div>
<pre class="code-body">git clone https://github.com/Questeria/helix &amp;&amp; cd helix
bash scripts/reproduce_trust.sh</pre>
            <div class="code-foot">
              <span>~1 minute · CPU-only</span>
              <span class="out">asserts: seed 9837db12 · fixpoint 0992dddd · DDC K1 84363adb</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>It runs green in CI on a clean GitHub runner on every push, so any third party can reproduce it from a fork. Full walkthrough on the <a href="/trust-chain/">trust chain</a> page.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PATH 3 — serve the live model on your own GPU -->
  <section>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="split">
        <div class="split-label">
          <span class="eyebrow">the real thing · your GPU</span>
          <h2>3 · Serve a real model live</h2>
          <p>This serves GPT-2-XL (1.5B) generating token by token on Helix-compiled CUDA kernels, with the live LIVE badge, the per-kernel trace, and the verification panel all driven by the actual backend.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="prose">
          <h3>What you need</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>An <strong>NVIDIA GPU</strong>, RTX 3070-class or better (<code>sm_86</code>, ~8&nbsp;GB VRAM).</li>
            <li><strong>WSL2 (Ubuntu) on Windows, or Linux</strong>, with the <strong>CUDA 12.x</strong> driver and a PTX-8.3-capable <code>ptxas</code> on <code>PATH</code> (<code>nvidia-smi</code> should list your GPU).</li>
            <li>The <strong>model weights</strong>, produced locally — see below. They are multi-gigabyte binaries, so they are not in the repository.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Get the weights (once)</h3>
          <p>The weights come from the <em>public</em> checkpoint on Hugging Face (<code>openai-community/gpt2-xl</code>, MIT-licensed) and are converted to the demo&rsquo;s flat format with a committed, <strong>Python-free</strong> importer. Nothing proprietary, nothing hidden:</p>
          <div class="code-card">
            <div class="code-head">
              <div class="dots" aria-hidden="true"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
              <span>bring your weights · committed importer</span>
            </div>
<pre class="code-body"># download openai-community/gpt2-xl (model.safetensors, vocab.json,
# merges.txt, config.json) from Hugging Face, then:
gcc -O2 helixc/runtime/gpt2_pack.c -o gpt2_pack
./gpt2_pack gpt2-xl/model.safetensors ~/gpt2_ext4/gpt2-xl.weights
mkdir -p helix-llm/models/gpt2-xl
cp gpt2-xl/&#123;vocab.json,merges.txt,config.json&#125; helix-llm/models/gpt2-xl/</pre>
            <div class="code-foot">
              <span>importer gated byte/bit-exact vs the originals</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>Start the server</h3>
          <div class="code-card">
            <div class="code-head">
              <div class="dots" aria-hidden="true"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
              <span>mints PTX from the 299-byte seed · builds worker + server · serves</span>
            </div>
<pre class="code-body">bash scripts/serve_chat_demo.sh
# then open  http://127.0.0.1:8848/?source=sse</pre>
            <div class="code-foot">
              <span>strictly serial GPU · Ctrl-C to stop</span>
              <span class="out">paths override via HELIX_SRC · HELIX_WORK · HELIX_XL_WEIGHTS</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>The launcher mints the GPU kernels fresh from the 299-byte seed, builds the no-Python C inference worker and HTTP/SSE server, then serves the demo with the weights resident. When a small instruction-tuned model and a base model are also present they are served alongside, and you can switch between them in the UI.</p>

          <p class="callout"><strong>On speed, stated plainly:</strong> live GPT-2-XL runs at roughly <strong>10 seconds per token</strong> (about 3 minutes for 20 tokens; measured 195.5&nbsp;s / 20 tokens in the gated run). This is a <em>verifiable execution layer</em>, not a fast inference engine — it leads with trust, never speed. The demo&rsquo;s preview animation mirrors that measured cadence so it is never painted faster than it really is.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="split-label" style="max-width: 60ch;">
        <span class="eyebrow">questions</span>
        <h2>Honest about the edges</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq" style="margin-top: 24px;">
        <details>
          <summary>Why aren&rsquo;t the model weights in the repository?</summary>
          <div class="faq-body"><p>They are multi-gigabyte binaries, and they are not the thing being proven. The <strong>trust core</strong> — the from-raw toolchain and its verification — is fully reproducible from the repository alone (step&nbsp;2). Only the GPT-2 demo legs need weights, and those are the unchanged <em>public</em> checkpoints from Hugging Face, converted by a committed, Python-free importer that is gated byte-for-byte against the originals. You bring the weights; the trust is in the repo.</p></div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Is it fast?</summary>
          <div class="faq-body"><p>No — and it does not pretend to be. GPT-2-XL runs at about 10&nbsp;s/token on this hardware. The point is <em>verifiable</em> execution: every kernel was compiled from a toolchain you can rebuild from 299 hand-typed bytes, and the output is matched token-for-token against an independent reference. Speed is a separate, later problem.</p></div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>I don&rsquo;t have an NVIDIA GPU.</summary>
          <div class="faq-body"><p>Two things still work with no GPU at all: the <a href="/helix-demo.zip" download>offline demo</a> (step&nbsp;1), which replays a real recorded run in any browser, and the <a href="/trust-chain/">trust-core verification</a> (step&nbsp;2), which is CPU-only. Only the live model in step&nbsp;3 needs the GPU.</p></div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>What does &ldquo;compiled from 299 bytes&rdquo; actually mean?</summary>
          <div class="faq-body"><p>The entire compiler toolchain bootstraps from a 299-byte hand-typed seed program, with no pre-existing compiler trusted along the way. The full chain, the diverse-double-compile scope, and the honestly-stated residuals are laid out on the <a href="/trust-chain/">trust chain</a> page.</p></div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cta dark">
    <div class="wrap">
      <span class="eyebrow">everything is public</span>
      <h2>Clone it, build it, check our work.</h2>
      <p>The whole project is one <code>git clone</code> away — toolchain, kernels, demo, and the scripts that prove it.</p>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="https://github.com/Questeria/helix">github.com/Questeria/helix <span class="arrow">&rarr;</span></a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/trust-chain/">See the trust chain</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/helix-demo.zip" download>Download the demo</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .callout {
    border: 1px solid var(--line2, #2a2a36);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--warn, #e0a44c);
    background: rgba(224, 164, 76, 0.06);
    border-radius: 10px;
    padding: 14px 16px;
    margin-top: 22px;
  }
  .prose ul { margin: 10px 0 16px; padding-left: 20px; }
  .prose li { margin: 7px 0; }
